How to make None and Some(unknown) output the same

# Combining `None` and `Some(unknown)` Arms

If you want both `None` and `Some(unknown)` to execute the same code, use the `_` (wildcard) pattern or combine them with `|`:

## Option 1: Wildcard pattern (most concise)
```rust
match env::args().nth(1).as_deref() {
    Some("generate") => run_generate(),
    _ => run_credential_builder(),  // handles both None and Some(unknown)
}
```

## Option 2: Explicit pattern combination
```rust
match env::args().nth(1).as_deref() {
    Some("generate") => run_generate(),
    None | Some(_) => run_credential_builder(),
}
```

## Option 3: If you want different behavior per case

Keep them separate but call the same function:
```rust
match env::args().nth(1).as_deref() {
    Some("generate") => run_generate(),
    Some(unknown) => show_error_and_exit(unknown),
    None => run_credential_builder(),
}
```

Then extract the error handling:
```rust
fn show_error_and_exit(unknown: &str) -> ! {
    eprintln!("error: unknown subcommand '{unknown}'");
    eprintln!();
    eprintln!("USAGE:\n    maglev [SUBCOMMAND]\n");
    eprintln!("SUBCOMMANDS:\n    generate    Interactively generate a .maglev config file\n    (none)      Run the credential builder (default)");
    std::process::exit(1);
}
```

**Note:** The first option silently treats unknown subcommands as "run credential builder", which may not be desired. The third option is usually better for error handling.
